Here is the comprehensive, updated master plan for your Statistical Backend-as-a-Service.

This plan synthesizes the architectural decisions we’ve made into a phased, executable roadmap. It focuses exclusively on building a 100% proprietary, enterprise-grade, on-premise Python engine that ingests raw Parquet data and outputs publication-ready, mathematically rigorous estimates.

The Architecture: "The Python Stat-Engine"
Before breaking down the phases, here is the finalized blueprint of the system you are building:

The Ingestion Standard: Strict Parquet-only data pipelines for lossless, high-speed memory management.

The Control Layer: A JSON "Metadata Contract" that acts as the universal language telling the engine what methodologies to apply.

The Orchestrator: FastAPI to handle internal routing and web requests.

The Math Engine: Polars (for lightning-fast data manipulation) and NumPy/SciPy (for complex matrix algebra and calibration), ensuring zero GPL-3.0 licensing conflicts.

The Deployment: Fully containerized via Docker for secure, air-gapped, on-premise installation at institutional clients.

Phase 1: The "Tracer Bullet" MVP (Edit & Imputation)
Goal: Build a single, functioning microservice that proves the end-to-end architecture works locally.
Focus: Steps 6.

Environment Setup

Initialize the project workspace in the Antigravity IDE.

Set up a Python virtual environment and install dependencies: polars, fastapi, uvicorn, and pytest.

The Metadata Schema Design

Finalize the test_payload.json structure to handle deterministic coherence rules (e.g., E001: Age vs. Marital Status) and probabilistic imputation parameters (e.g., nearest neighbor donor classes).

The Core Engine (engine.py)

Write the Polars logic to parse the JSON coherence rules into lazy-evaluated filters.

Implement the first imputation algorithm (e.g., hot-deck or nearest-neighbor) natively in Python.

The API Gateway (api.py)

Wrap the engine in a FastAPI endpoint (POST /api/v1/impute).

Configure it to accept the JSON payload and the path to the Parquet file.

Quality Control Validation

Generate a simulated "Golden" Parquet dataset.

Inject controlled missingness (MCAR and MAR).

Run the dataset through the API and use pytest to mathematically verify the imputation accuracy against the golden dataset.

Phase 2: The Rigorous Math (Calibration & Estimation)
Goal: Translate complex official statistical methodology into a pure Python library to establish your proprietary IP moat.
Focus: Steps 7 & 8.

Weighting & Calibration Engine

Build the ingestion logic for auxiliary/benchmark totals.

Translate Generalized Regression (GREG) estimators and raking ratio methodologies into NumPy matrix operations to calculate non-response adjustments and final calibration weights.

Complex Variance Estimation

Implement Taylor series linearization for standard complex survey designs.

Build modules for replicate weight methods (Bootstrap, Jackknife, BRR) to handle situations where linearization isn't feasible.

Microservice Integration

Create a new FastAPI endpoint (POST /api/v1/estimate) that receives the imputed Parquet file from Phase 1 and the calibration JSON, outputting the final weighted point estimates and their variances.

Phase 3: The Enterprise Wrapper (Confidentiality & Output)
Goal: Make the software compliant with the strict data privacy laws required by institutional and government clients.
Focus: Steps 9 & 10.

Disclosure Control Algorithms

Develop the logic to evaluate the weighted final tables against minimum cell count thresholds.

Implement primary and secondary cell suppression algorithms to prevent reverse-engineering of microdata.

Automated QA Reporting

Build a reporting script that logs the entire pipeline's lifecycle.

Output a structured summary detailing imputation rates (by variable), calibration convergence diagnostics, and a list of cells suppressed for confidentiality.

Docker Containerization

Write the Dockerfile and docker-compose.yml.

Package the entire FastAPI, Polars, and NumPy stack into a deployable container image, ensuring it runs flawlessly in a completely offline environment.

Phase 4: The AI Orchestration (The "Brain")
Goal: Abstract the complex JSON parameters away from the end-user so the platform can be operated using plain-English objectives.
Focus: Front-end AI routing and the Metadata Loophole.

The AI Prompt Architecture

Design the system prompts to act as a "Lead Methodologist."

Configure the AI to accept a data dictionary and plain-English goals, outputting the strict JSON Metadata Contract required by your Python backend.

Hybrid Model Routing

Set up a routing layer that sends heavy logical reasoning (drafting the initial statistical strategy) to a high-capacity model (Gemini 3.1 Pro).

Route lighter, rapid formatting tasks (like parsing the QA report for the user dashboard) to a faster, quota-efficient model (Gemini Flash).

The "Metadata Loophole" Implementation

Ensure the architecture strictly separates the data. The cloud AI only ever sees variable names and metadata, while the highly confidential Parquet microdata never leaves the client's on-premise Docker container.

Phase 5: Advanced Modeling & Deep Integration (SAE, HB, SDC)
Goal: Elevate the platform to handle the most complex statistical tasks including Small Area Estimation and Exact Optimal Disclosure Control.

Small-Area Estimation (SAE) & Hierarchical Bayes (HB)
- Implement EBLUP (Empirical Best Linear Unbiased Prediction) for area-level and unit-level models.
- Build a full Hierarchical Bayes engine with Gibbs sampling and Metropolis-Hastings for robust inference in data-scarce domains.

Statistical Disclosure Control (SDC)
- Implement simultaneous multi-cell protection using Exact Optimal MILP solvers.
- Build automated audit routines to mathematically verify the safety of published tables.

Final Pipeline Integration
- Unified PipelineManager orchestrating all 8 modules (A-H).
- End-to-end "one-click" execution from raw Parquet to SDC-protected outputs.
- Comprehensive QA reporting integrating diagnostics from all simulation and optimization steps.

